5. What is a Bean?

Definition
A Bean is:
An object that is created and managed by Spring container.

Example
@Component
public class Apple { }

Apple object → Bean
------------------------------------------------------------

6. Ways to Create Beans?

Method 1 → @Component
Meaning:Automatically creates bean using component scanning.

Example
@Component
public class Mobile { }

Used for
Our own classes

Method 2 → @Bean
Meaning:Manual bean creation inside configuration class.

Example
@Bean
public Scanner scanner() {
    return new Scanner(System.in);
}

Used for
Third-party classes
Inbuilt classes
Collections
When source code cannot be modified

Difference: @Component vs @Bean
Feature		@Component	@Bean
Type		Automatic	Manual
Location	Class		Method
Use		Our classes	External classes
----------------------------------------------------------

7. @Configuration

Definition
Marks a class as:
Spring configuration class

Example:

@Configuration
public class MyConfig { }

Used to define:@Bean methods
Application settings
-----------------------------------------------

8. Dependency Injection (DI)

Definition
DI means::Supplying required objects to another object automatically.

Example
Customer needs Mobile
Instead of:
Customer creates Mobile

Spring:Spring gives Mobile to Customer
-----------------------------------------------------\

9. Types of Dependency Injection

1.Field Injection
@Autowired
Mobile mob;

Pros: Easy
Cons:Hard to test,Not recommended

2️.Setter Injection
@Autowired
public void setMobile(Mobile m)

Pros:Optional dependencies

3️.Constructor Injection (BEST PRACTICE)
@Autowired
public Customer(Mobile m)

Pros
✔ Mandatory dependencies
✔ Safe
✔ Test friendly
✔ Recommended
